---
import '../../styles/global.css';
import LessonLayout from '../../layouts/LessonLayout.astro';
import LessonHeader from '../../components/LessonHeader.astro';
import LessonNav from '../../components/LessonNav.astro';
import InsightBox from '../../components/InsightBox.astro';
import TagBadge from '../../components/TagBadge.astro';
import LocalGradientDemo from '../../components/demos/LocalGradientDemo.astro';
---

<LessonLayout title="Local Gradients" lessonNumber="1.4" section="The Graph">

    <LessonHeader lessonNumber="1.4" title="Local Gradients" description="Each operation knows one small thing: how its own output reacts to each of its own inputs. That little fact, attached to every node, is all backprop needs. The chain rule does the rest.">
        <TagBadge variant="math">math</TagBadge>
        <TagBadge variant="default">9 min read</TagBadge>
    </LessonHeader>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">What "local" means.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            A <strong>local gradient</strong> is an operation's answer to the nudge question about <em>only itself</em>:
            "if I wiggle one of my inputs a hair, how does my output move?" It ignores the rest of the graph entirely.
            A multiply node doesn't know or care what happens ten steps downstream — it only knows its own rule.
        </p>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            This is the per-operation derivative from lesson 0.3, now thought of as a property attached to each node.
            Every operation carries its own little rule.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">The rules you'll need.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            A scalar neural net needs only a handful. Each row says: given the output's gradient, what's the local
            factor for each input?
        </p>
        <div class="bg-white border border-mt-border rounded-xl overflow-hidden mb-4">
            <table class="w-full text-sm">
                <thead><tr class="bg-mt-bg text-left"><th class="px-5 py-2 font-semibold">Operation</th><th class="px-5 py-2 font-semibold">Local gradient</th><th class="px-5 py-2 font-semibold">In words</th></tr></thead>
                <tbody class="divide-y divide-mt-border font-mono text-xs">
                    <tr><td class="px-5 py-2">c = a + b</td><td class="px-5 py-2">&part;c/&part;a = 1, &part;c/&part;b = 1</td><td class="px-5 py-2 font-sans text-mt-muted">a sum passes gradient straight through</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="px-5 py-2">c = a &times; b</td><td class="px-5 py-2">&part;c/&part;a = b, &part;c/&part;b = a</td><td class="px-5 py-2 font-sans text-mt-muted">each input's factor is the other input</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="px-5 py-2">c = a&#8319;</td><td class="px-5 py-2">&part;c/&part;a = n&middot;a&#8319;&#8315;&sup1;</td><td class="px-5 py-2 font-sans text-mt-muted">the power rule</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="px-5 py-2">c = tanh(a)</td><td class="px-5 py-2">&part;c/&part;a = 1 &minus; c&sup2;</td><td class="px-5 py-2 font-sans text-mt-muted">flat when saturated, steep near 0</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="px-5 py-2">c = relu(a)</td><td class="px-5 py-2">&part;c/&part;a = 1 if a&gt;0 else 0</td><td class="px-5 py-2 font-sans text-mt-muted">on or off, like a gate</td></tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed">
            Notice the multiply and add rules are exactly what we found by hand in lessons 0.1 and 0.5. Nothing new —
            just collected in one place and labeled "local."
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">A worked node.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Take the multiply <span class="font-mono">d = a &times; b</span> with <span class="font-mono">a = 2,
            b = -3</span>. Its local gradients:
        </p>
        <div class="bg-white border border-mt-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-4 font-mono text-sm space-y-1">
            <div>&part;d/&part;a = b = -3 &nbsp; <span class="font-sans text-mt-muted">(wiggle a, d moves at rate -3)</span></div>
            <div>&part;d/&part;b = a = &nbsp;2 &nbsp; <span class="font-sans text-mt-muted">(wiggle b, d moves at rate 2)</span></div>
        </div>

        <LocalGradientDemo />
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed">
            The node can produce these from the values it already remembered during the forward pass. It needs nothing
            else.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">The design this points to.</h2>
        <InsightBox>
            <p class="text-sm">Every node stores two things from the forward pass: its <strong>output value</strong> and
            enough to compute its <strong>local gradients</strong>. Backprop then chains these together — multiply local
            gradients along each edge, add where paths merge (lesson 0.5). That single idea is the entire engine you'll
            build. The next unit turns "chain the locals together" into a concrete walk over the graph.</p>
        </InsightBox>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Key takeaways</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">1</span></div><p class="text-sm">A local gradient is one operation's "if my input wiggles, how does my output move?" — ignoring the rest of the graph.</p></div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">2</span></div><p class="text-sm">You only need a handful of rules: add, multiply, power, and a couple of activations.</p></div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">3</span></div><p class="text-sm">Each node stores its value and local gradients; backprop chains them with multiply-along, add-across.</p></div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <LessonNav
        prevHref="/graph/parameters-vs-activations" prevLabel="Prev: Parameters vs Activations"
        nextHref="/backprop/the-backward-pass" nextLabel="Next: The Backward Pass"
    />

</LessonLayout>
